<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-09-16T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-09-16T16:00:00-05:00" n="94" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d94">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">810.20 Defense/9–1640:
                                    Telegram</note>
                                <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Colombia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Braden</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                            State</gloss></hi></head>
                                <opener>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Bogotá</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-09-16T16:00:00-05:00">September 16, 1940—4
                                            p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 5:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p>273. My telegram No. 270, September 14 [<hi rend="italic">15</hi>], 1940. In an hour’s conversation with Minister of War
                                    this morning, it was agreed I should prepare for him memorandum
                                    of all points we desire covered in staff agreement. Based on
                                    this, he will endeavor to draft the latter and will have further
                                    consultations with me thereon.</p>
                                <p>Two points emphasized by Minister of War were: <list>
                                        <label>1.</label>
                                        <item>Delicate political situation necessitates utmost
                                            caution by Colombian Government in these matters.</item>
                                        <label>2.</label>
                                        <item>What Colombian Government can and will guarantee
                                            without reservation is to maintain internal order and
                                            that there shall never be an attack on the Canal from
                                            its territory.</item>
                                    </list></p>
                                <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Braden</hi></signed></closer>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>